\parai{Expressivity} refers to the ability to express and respond to potentially complex requests.
 KGs support expressive query languages that can join data across relations, group entities by categories such as geo-regions, compute aggregates (e.g., averaging) over groups, and much more
 [DBLP:journals/csur/AnglesABHRV17].
 LLMs and SEs can process arbitrary requests in natural language (with varying success). 
 For SEs, these are traditionally in the form of keywords, but telegraphic queries and full-fledged questions are equally supported today. However, the input length is tightly limited.
 LLMs, on the other hand, accept fairly long user text (e.g., 50K tokens and increasing), which allows natural conversations and even working with user-provided data such as spreadsheets.
 But operating over text has pros and cons.
 LLMs 
 can capture nuanced expressions that are difficult to model in KGs.
 On the other hand, KGs feature formal types and logical operators, with unambiguous interpretations not possible for text.
 For example, negating a statement can be very subtle and tricky to understand in language, whereas it is explicit and clear in logic.